public class TreeNode {
    int val;
    TreeNode left;
    TreeNode right;
    TreeNode(int x) { val = x; }
}

class Solution {
    int sum = 0;

    public TreeNode convertBST(TreeNode root) {
        if (root != null) {
            convertBST(root.right);
            sum += root.val;
            root.val = sum;
            convertBST(root.left);
        }

        return root;
    }
}
```

    We traverse the tree in a right-to-left inorder traversal using a recursive algorithm. This traversal ensures we visit the nodes with the greater keys first. During this traversal, we maintain a running sum of the values of the nodes we've visited so far. When we visit a new node, we add the running sum to it and update the running sum with the new node's value. This effectively converts the tree into a Greater Tree, as the nodes' values are replaced with the sum of all the values greater than their initial values. This solution has a time complexity of O(n), where n is the number of nodes in the tree.
